The dataset âavocadoâ consists of weekly retail scan data for National retain volume and price. The data is based on retail sales of Hass avocados directly from cash registers. Each row is an observation from a singular day in a certain location/geography. The columns, or rather âvariablesâ of the data set include the following: date, average_price, type, year, geography, total_volume, 4046, 4225, 4770. The date variable displays the date of when the observation was made, the average_price variable in the table represents a âper avocadoâ cost, type is whether the avocado is conventional or organic, year is the year of the observation, geography is the city or region of the observation, and total_volume is the total number of avocados sold. The 4046 variable is the total number of small Hass avocados with PLU 4046 sold, 4225 is the total number of large Hass avocados with PLU 4225 sold, and 4770 is the total number of extra large Hass avocados with PLU 4770 sold. âPLUâ is the Product Lookup codes and are only for Hass avocados. Other variables include total_bags, small_bags, large_bags, and xlarge_bags. The dataset includes 13 variables and 33045 obervations.

  1. Clean the data in any way you see fit.
Code 
# Filter out rows where geography is not "Total U.S." and rename PLU columns
avocado_clean = avocado[avocado['geography'] != "Total U.S."].rename(columns={
    '4046': 'small_hass',
    '4225': 'large_hass',
    '4770': 'xl_hass',
})
# avocado_clean: The cleaned data without "Total U.S." and with renamed columns

# major_regions: Data from major regions
# Filter for major regions
major_regions = avocado_clean[avocado_clean['geography'].isin([
    "Northeast", "Southeast", "South Central", "Midsouth", "West", "Plains", "Great Lakes"
])]

# states: Data from specific states
# Filter for states
states = avocado_clean[avocado_clean['geography'].isin([
    "New York", "California", "West Tex/New Mexico", "South Carolina", "Northern New England"
])]

# small_regions: Data from all the remaining smaller regions, excluding major regions and specific states
# Filter for small regions by excluding major regions and states
small_regions = avocado_clean[
    ~avocado_clean['geography'].isin(major_regions['geography']) &
    ~avocado_clean['geography'].isin(states['geography'
])]

  1. Which major geographical region sold the most total organic, small Hass avocados in 2017?
Code 
# Filter, group, and find the region with the most organic, small Hass avocados sold in 2017
top_region = (avocado_clean[(avocado_clean['year'] == 2017) & 
                            (avocado_clean['type'] == 'organic') & 
                            (avocado_clean['geography'].isin(["Northeast", "Southeast", "South Central", "Midsouth", "West", "Plains", "Great Lakes"]))]
              .groupby('geography', observed=True)['small_hass'] # Groups the data by region and focuses on the small_hass column
              .sum() # Sums up the total number of small Hass avocados sold for each region
              .idxmax()) # Finds the region name with the max value

top_value = (avocado_clean[(avocado_clean['year'] == 2017) & 
                           (avocado_clean['type'] == 'organic') & 
                           (avocado_clean['geography'].isin(["Northeast", "Southeast", "South Central", "Midsouth", "West", "Plains", "Great Lakes"]))]
             .groupby('geography', observed=True)['small_hass']
             .sum()
             .max()) # Finds the largest (maximum) value among the summed totals

print(top_region)
print(top_value)

  1. Split the date variable into month, day, and year variables. In which month is the highest average volume of avocado sales?

# Convert 'date' to datetime format
avocado_clean['date'] = pd.to_datetime(avocado_clean['date'])

# Split date into 'month', 'day', and 'year'
avocado_clean['month'] = avocado_clean['date'].dt.month
avocado_clean['day'] = avocado_clean['date'].dt.day
avocado_clean['year'] = avocado_clean['date'].dt.year

# Group by 'month' and calculate the average volume of avocado sales
avg_volume = avocado_clean.groupby('month')['total_volume'].mean()

# Find the month with the highest average volume
top_month = avg_volume.idxmax()
top_volume = avg_volume.max()

print(top_month)
print(top_volume)

  1. In which California regions is the price of organic versus conventional avocados most different? Support your answer with a few summary statistics AND a visualization.

# Group by 'geography' and 'type', and calculate mean price
avg_price_by_type = cali.groupby(['geography', 'type'],  observed=True)['average_price'].mean().reset_index()

# Pivot the data so that 'organic' and 'conventional' are separate columns
pivot_cali = avg_price_by_type.pivot(index='geography', columns='type', values='average_price').reset_index()

# Calculate the price difference between organic and conventional avocados
pivot_cali['price_difference'] = pivot_cali['organic'] - pivot_cali['conventional']

  1. The following plot shows, for all four California regions, the proportion of the average Hass avocado sales that are small, large, or extra large; conventional vs.Â organic. Recreate the plot; you do not have to replicate the exact finishing touches - e.g., color, theme - but your plot should resemble the content of this plot.
Code 
# Melt cali to transform 'small_hass', 'large_hass', and 'xl_hass' into a long format
cali_melted = cali.melt(id_vars=['geography', 'type'], 
                      value_vars=['small_hass', 'large_hass', 'xl_hass'], 
                      var_name='hass', 
                      value_name='sales_amount')

# Group by geography (city), type, and hass (size), then sum the amounts
cali_grouped = cali_melted.groupby(['geography', 'type', 'hass']).agg(sum_amount=('sales_amount', 'sum')).reset_index()
cali_grouped.head()
# Source for .agg(): https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/version/0.22/generated/pandas.core.groupby.DataFrameGroupBy.agg.html

# Make 'hass' ordinal to match plot being recreated
cali_grouped['hass'] = pd.Categorical(cali_grouped['hass'], 
                                      categories=['xl_hass', 'large_hass', 'small_hass'], 
                                      ordered=True)
# Source: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/user_guide/categorical.html

# Create plot
(ggplot(cali_grouped, aes(x='geography', y='sum_amount', fill='hass')) +
     geom_bar(stat='identity', position='fill') +
     facet_wrap('~type') +
     labs(title='Proportion of Average Hass Avocado Sales by Size',
          x='Region of California',
          y='Proportion',
          fill='size') +
     scale_fill_discrete(labels=['Xlarge', 'Large', 'Small']) +
     scale_y_continuous(breaks=[0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1],
                         labels=['0%', '25%', '50%', '75%', '100%']) +
     theme_bw() +
     theme(axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1)))

Using Outside

A joke in the media is that Millennials canât afford houses, because they spend all their money buying avocado toast. Letâs use this data set to address that claim.

Find or make a data set with house prices for these four California regions. Join this data set with your California avocado data set.

Use your new joined data set to make an argument about the relationship between house prices and avocado prices/sales.

Support your argument with a plot.

Code 
housing = pd.read_csv('Metro_zhvi_uc_sfrcondo_tier_0.33_0.67_sm_sa_month.csv')
# Source: https://www.zillow.com/research/data/

# Split the "RegionName" column into "geography" and "state"
housing[['geography', 'state']] = housing['RegionName'].str.split(',', expand=True)
# Source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/63796316/string-split-with-expand-true-can-anyone-explain-what-is-the-meaning

# Filter for CA regions
ca_housing = housing[housing['geography'].isin(["Los Angeles-Long Beach-Anaheim", "San Francisco", "San Diego", "Sacramento"])]

# Replace LA variable name to match cali data set
ca_housing.loc[:, 'geography'] = ca_housing['geography'].replace({
    "Los Angeles-Long Beach-Anaheim": "Los Angeles"
})

# Unpivot the date columns into two columns: "date" and "house_price"
date_columns = ca_housing.loc[:, '2000-01-31':'2021-12-31'] # date column range for this data set
ca_housing_long = pd.melt(ca_housing, id_vars=['geography', 'state'], value_vars=date_columns.columns, 
                          var_name='date', value_name='house_price')

# Separate "date" into "year", "month", and "day"
ca_housing_long[['year', 'month', 'day']] = ca_housing_long['date'].str.split('-', expand=True)

# Filter for specific years, remove missing values
ca_housing_filtered = ca_housing_long[
    (ca_housing_long['year'].isin(['2015', '2016', '2017', '2018', '2019', '2020'])) &
    (~ca_housing_long['geography'].isna()) &
    (~ca_housing_long['year'].isna()) &
    (~ca_housing_long['house_price'].isna())
]

# ca_housing_filtered.head()
Code 
# Check the data types to ensure they're the same
# print(cali.dtypes)

Code 
# Make a copy of the DataFrames to avoid SettingWithCopyWarning
cali = cali.copy()
ca_housing_filtered = ca_housing_filtered.copy()

# Convert the 'year' column in both DataFrames to int using .loc[]
cali.loc[:, 'year'] = cali['year'].astype(object)
ca_housing_filtered.loc[:, 'year'] = ca_housing_filtered['year'].astype(int)

# Kept getting 'FutureWarning: Setting an item of incompatible dtype is deprecated and will raise in a future error of pandas'
# ChatGPT 4o suggestion: Ensure 'geography' column has no leading/trailing spaces
ca_housing_filtered['geography'] = ca_housing_filtered['geography'].str.strip()
cali['geography'] = cali['geography'].str.strip()

# Merge the two datasets
avo_housing = cali.merge(ca_housing_filtered, on=["geography", "year"], how="inner")

# avo_housing.head()
Code 
# Make boxplots
(ggplot(avo_housing, aes(x='house_price', y='average_price', fill='year')) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    facet_wrap('~geography') +  # Create facets for each region
    labs(title="Relationship between Avocado and Housing Prices",
         subtitle="Separated by Region",
         x="Average Price of Homes ($)",
         y="Average Price of Avocados ($)",
         fill="Year") +
    theme_bw()
)

The plot shows no clear evidence that avocado prices are linked to housing prices across different California regions. For example, in San Francisco, housing prices are significantly higher than in other regions, yet the avocado prices do not vary drastically across the years. Similarly, in Los Angeles and San Diego, avocado prices fluctuate, but there is no direct relationship with the rising or falling house prices. This suggests that the idea that Millennials canât afford houses due to spending on avocados is not supported by the data.
